{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569295"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22060"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22060"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.2,0.41,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106438"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15021"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88894"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2975"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5884"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106438"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of irregular menstrual periods and occasional milky discharge from both breasts. Over the past two weeks, she has noticed difficulty seeing objects in her peripheral vision, particularly when driving. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is not pregnant and is not breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual field testing by confrontation reveals bitemporal hemianopia. Bilateral galactorrhoea is confirmed on breast examination. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal prolactin 4800 mU/L (102-496), with normal thyroid function tests and negative pregnancy test. MRI brain shows a 22 mm pituitary macroadenoma with suprasellar extension and chiasmal compression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cabergoline","Bromocriptine","Transsphenoidal surgery","Radiotherapy","Octreotide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a prolactin-secreting pituitary macroadenoma causing both endocrine symptoms (galactorrhoea, menstrual irregularity) and mass effect (bitemporal hemianopia from chiasmal compression). The markedly elevated prolactin level (\u0026gt;4000 mU/L) confirms a prolactinoma rather than stalk effect from a non-functioning adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECabergoline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. It is a dopamine agonist that effectively reduces prolactin levels and tumour size in over 80% of patients. Even in the presence of visual field defects, medical therapy is first-line as most prolactinomas respond rapidly, with visual improvement often occurring within days to weeks. Cabergoline is preferred over bromocriptine due to better tolerability and more convenient dosing (once or twice weekly versus daily).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBromocriptine\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative dopamine agonist but is less well tolerated than cabergoline, with more frequent side effects including nausea, postural hypotension, and headaches. It requires daily dosing and is now considered second-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranssphenoidal surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients who fail medical therapy, cannot tolerate dopamine agonists, or have rapidly progressive visual loss. While this patient has visual field defects, medical therapy should be trialled first as most patients respond well. Surgery may be considered if there is no improvement after several weeks of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is third-line treatment for prolactinomas, used only when both medical therapy and surgery have failed. It has a slow onset of action (months to years) and carries risks of hypopituitarism and secondary tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOctreotide\u003C/strong\u003E is a somatostatin analogue used primarily for growth hormone-secreting adenomas (acromegaly) and has no role in managing prolactinomas. It does not effectively reduce prolactin levels or tumour size in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing initiation of cabergoline, this patient requires close monitoring with repeat prolactin levels and visual field assessment. Most patients show significant improvement within 2-4 weeks. Urgent neurosurgical referral would be indicated if visual deterioration continues despite medical therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cabergoline is the first-line medical treatment for prolactinomas, even those causing visual field defects.","Visual field defects from pituitary macroadenomas typically present as bitemporal hemianopia due to chiasmal compression.","Most prolactinomas respond well to dopamine agonist therapy, with surgery reserved for medication-resistant cases or acute visual deterioration."],"references":["Pituitary disease: An update. Australian Journal of General Practice.\u202f2021;50(1\u20132):30\u201335. Reprinted on RACGP website. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/050817b1-ec39-4d96-bb9e-25a297c2ae0f/Pituitary-disease-An-update.aspx.","Rajini Kanth R. Yatavelli, Kamal Bhusal. Prolactinoma. In: StatPearls [online]. 2018. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459347/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88894"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22060"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88894"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T20:21:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T14:57:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15021"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106438"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},